article.description:
Eddie Jones did everything possible in the 
fourth quarter to help the Miami Heat defeat the Houston
Rockets.  But Steve Francis responded - twice.
article.headline: Big game from Eddie Jones not enough for Heat
article.linkText: Francis comes up clutch as Rockets survive Heat blitz
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- With the game on the line, the Houston Rockets put the ball in the hands of Mr. Clutch. Once again, Steve Francis didn't disappoint. Francis forced overtime with a buzzer-beating 3-pointer for the second time in less than a week, then came up with a key loose ball to help the Houston Rockets defeat the Miami Heat 105-100 Tuesday night. Francis, who scored 21 points, sent the game into overtime by hitting a 25-footer to tie the game at 91-all. The shot was similar to the one Francis hit at the end of regulation Monday night against Memphis in a 114-109 overtime loss. With five seconds left, Francis ran around a pick set by center Yao Ming and launched a shot over Brian Grant just before the buzzer sounded. The ball swished through. "We run that play a lot at the end of the game," Francis said. "We knew Miami is known for being a tough defensive team. It's a tough play. Brian Grant was right there. He might have nipped my hand, but I had enough elevation. "Once it left my hand, I knew it was good." With the Rockets leading 101-100, Miami's Eddie Jones lost possession with the clock winding down, and Francis came up with the ball. Eddie Griffin hit a pair of free throws with 9 seconds left to push Houston's lead to 103-100. Following a miss from the corner by Mike James, Yao added a pair of free throws to help the Rockets snap a two-game losing streak. "I knew this was going to be a tough game," Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. "The Heat is a very physical team with a lot of veteran players that I have respect for. This was a heck of a game. For the coaches, a game like this takes days and years off your life." Cuttino Mobley scored 27 points for the Rockets, and Yao had 15 points and 12 rebounds. Griffin and Glen Rice added 15 apiece for the Rockets. Jones scored 32 points for the Heat, including 17 in the fourth quarter as Miami rallied from a 14-point deficit. Jones also added 10 rebounds, seven assists and six steals. In his last four games, Jones has scored 33, 24, 38 and 32 points. "You have to win it down the stretch," Jones said. "We did the job in the fourth quarter. We could have played better, but it just didn't go our way. "We knew exactly what they were going to run at the end. We saw it about four or five times on tape. Brian was all over him, and (Francis) hit a tough shot. You have to give him credit for that." Travis Best scored on an off-balance drive with 23 seconds left to give the Heat an 89-88 lead, and Jones hit a pair of free throws to push the lead to 91-88 with five seconds to go. With one last possession, Francis worked around a screen from Yao and let fly just before time expired. After leading 46-40 at halftime, the Rockets closed the third quarter with a 15-7 run to extend their lead to 75-63. Jones brought the Heat back, scoring 12 straight points to cut the gap to 77-75 with 7:05 left in the fourth. Included was a 3-pointer and three foul shots when he was hacked on a 3-point attempt. Rookie Caron Butler scored 18 points and Brian Grant added 16 for Miami, which has lost six of its last seven, including three of four at home. "We fought like hell to get back in the game," Heat coach Pat Riley said. "It came down to that shot and it got them into overtime. We didn't have enough left. A 3-point lead with five seconds left, it comes down to make or miss." Game notes
Butler had a steal, extending his streak to 19 games, the longest current streak in the NBA. ... Houston snapped a three-game losing streak to Miami and won for only the third time in the last 14 meetings. ... Yao has double-doubles in six of his last seven games. ... Jones started 4-for-4, then missed his next eight. ...The Rockets have played three overtime games in their last six contests, winning once.
